[4
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 06:16:26 -1000
From: Richard Frankel <rfrankel@hawaii.edu>

While I have no disagreement with the first three comments, they seem to
equate sushi with raw fish. Perhaps there is some confusion with sashimi,
which is indeed raw fish. Some sushi includes sashimi, but there are many
varieties of sushi which do not contain any raw fish. Rice is the basic
ingredient. Thus the health concerns are broader than those associated with
raw fish.
The primary concern in Hawaii related to sushi prepared in advance (as
opposed to prepared-to-order at a sushi bar) and then stored for some time
without refrigeration. This allowed for growth of potential
gastrointestinal pathogens or toxin-producing microorganisms, as the rice is
generally shaped by hand, and the sushi may contain egg, raw vegetables, and
a wide variety of foods.
--
